        {
          "id": 73645,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is a treatment option for amblyopia</span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">All are true regarding penalization except:</span></span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q1091208",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31572,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Done in squinting eye</span></strong> </span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Penalization&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">is a <strong>process of blurring the NORMAL eye with atropine</strong>. </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">It is <strong>done in the treatment of mild&ndash;moderate amblyopia</strong> (6/24 or better), especially when due to <strong>anisometropic hypermetropia.</strong> </span></span></span></li>\r\n\t<li style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Patch occlusion is more advantageous</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">. Hence penalization done in children non-compliant to patching. </span></span></span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/08/07/whatsapp-image-2023-06-12-at-19012101101099.jpg\" style=\"height:735px; width:1000px\" /></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Useful in very young children</strong>: This is <strong>true</strong>. Penalization is often used in young children as a treatment for amblyopia, especially when patching therapy is not feasible or not tolerated.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>This procedure uses atropine: True</strong>. Atropine is used in penalization therapy to blur the vision in the non-amblyopic eye by dilating the pupil and paralyzing the accommodation, thereby forcing the amblyopic eye to work harder and improve.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>It is a treatment option for amblyopia: True</strong>. Penalization is a well-recognized treatment option for amblyopia, particularly in cases where traditional patching is not suitable or effective.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Penalization therapy for amblyopia involves applying atropine to the non-amblyopic&nbsp;</span></strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">(non-squinting) <strong>eye to blur its vision</strong> and <strong>stimulate use of the amblyopic</strong> (squinting) <strong>eye</strong>, making it an effective treatment in very young children.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: KANSKI 9<sup>TH</sup> EDITION PG.NO 708</span></strong></span></span></p>",
