        {
          "id": 73678,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Malingering </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73679,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Amblyopia </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73680,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Retrobulbar neuritis </span></span></span></p>"
        },
        {
          "id": 73681,
          "text": "<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Refractive accommodative esotropia </span></span></span></p>"
        }
      ],
      "text": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><span style=\"font-family:&quot;Calibri&quot;,sans-serif\">A 14-year-old boy presented with complaints of defective vision. His best corrected visual acuity in right eye was 6/6 and in left eye was 6/60. Retinoscopy revealed +1D in right eye and +7D in left eye. Ocular examination was within normal limits. The probable diagnosis would be?</span></span></p>",
      "unique_key": "Q3797091",
      "question_audio": null,
      "question_video": null,
      "map_id": 31573,
      "difficulty_level": "intermediate",
      "subjects_id": [
        8
      ],
      "solution": "<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ans. B) Amblyopia</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Option B:</span></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">This scenario is suggestive of <strong>Anisometropic amblyopia.</strong></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://cerebellum-web-static.s3.amazonaws.com/media/public/images/2023/08/07/whatsapp-image-2023-06-12-at-190121011010201.jpg\" style=\"height:1379px; width:1000px\" /></span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Explanation:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option A.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Malingering:</strong> This would imply the <strong>patient is feigning or exaggerating the extent of visual impairment</strong>. However, the significant difference in refractive error between the eyes and the corresponding difference in visual acuity suggest a genuine visual problem, making malingering unlikely.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option C.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Retrobulbar Neuritis</strong>: This condition typically <strong>presents with pain on eye movement and a rapid reduction in visual acuity</strong>, often associated with <strong>color vision impairment</strong>. There&#39;s no indication of these symptoms from the given information.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12pt\"><strong>Option D.</strong>&nbsp;</span><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\"><strong>Refractive Accommodative Esotropia</strong>: This condition is <strong>characterized by esotropia</strong> (inward turning of the eye) that is <strong>caused primarily by uncorrected hyperopia</strong> (farsightedness). While the patient has hyperopia in the left eye, there&#39;s no mention of esotropia.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Educational Objective:</span></u></strong></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">The <strong>most probable diagnosis in this case is amblyopia</strong>, likely <strong>anisometropic amblyopia</strong>, due to a significant uncorrected refractive difference between the two eyes during a critical period of visual development.</span></span></span></p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\">&nbsp;</p>\r\n\r\n<p style=\"text-align:justify\"><span style=\"font-size:11pt\"><span style=\"font-family:Calibri,sans-serif\"><strong><u><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">Ref</span></u></strong><strong><span style=\"font-size:12.0pt\">: KHURANA COMPREHENSIVE OPHTHALMOLOGY 5<sup>TH</sup> EDITION pg.no: 339</span></strong></span></span></p>",
